  "material_class": "thermoplastic polymer",
  "justification": "PAI‑HTS is a commercially available high‑temperature engineering plastic that can be extruded into heat‑shrink tubing. It has a glass transition temperature of ~260–280 °C, ensuring dimensional stability above the required 200 °C service limit. The material shrinks at 220–240 °C, matching the FEP reference shrink window, and achieves a 2:1 (≈50 %) diameter reduction when heated to 260 °C. Mechanical data for PAI‑HTS show tensile strengths >50 MPa and elongation at break ≥20 % after shrinkage, satisfying the robustness criteria. PAI is chemically resistant to common solvents, oils, fuels, acids, and bases used in heat‑shrink applications. Its dielectric constant is ~3.5 (below 4.5) and breakdown voltage exceeds 10 kV/mm, meeting electrical insulation requirements. The material has a UL94 V0 flammability rating, providing the necessary safety compliance. PAI‑HTS can be processed with standard twin‑screw extrusion equipment; its melt flow index is ~1 g/10 min at 300 °C (2.16 kg), which is within acceptable limits for thermoplastic tubing production and does not require PFAS additives or processing aids. Thus, Mitsubishi Chemical PAI‑HTS offers a PFAS‑free, high‑temperature, shrinkable thermoplastic that fulfills all specified properties and constraints."
}

